>>>>>>> In May 2012, newspapers picked up on a study into dieting during
pregnancy. The Independent claimed “Dieting is good for you”, while the Daily
Mail insisted “piling on the pounds during pregnancy” increases the risk of
>>>>>>> Researchers at Queen Mary, University of London, have shown that
dieting during pregnancy has no adverse effects on the birth weight of newborn
babies and is the most effective way for obese or overweight women to reduce
the weight gain that can lead to complications such as gestational diabetes.
>>>>>>> Their research was published in the ‘British Medical Journal’.
>>>>>>> ‘Eating for two’ and piling on excess weight during pregnancy is
discouraged by doctors, since it increases the risk of complications such as
>>>>>>> However, many women worry that dieting could harm their unborn child,
and doctors are often cautious about advising on ways to manage weight. The
research studied the effect of diet, exercise, or a combination of the two, on
the amount of weight that women gained during their pregnancies and whether
>>>>>>> All three methods reduced weight gain but dieting had the greatest
impact. Dieting also seemed to reduce the risk of complications and did not
>>>>>>> Not all pregnant women need to follow calorie-controlled diets to
